ry of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705192,"age":5,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705193,"age":14,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Sir Alan Buxhull was born about 1323, in Sussex, England, his father, Sir Alan Bokeshull of Buxhull, was 29 and his mother, Maude Bokeshull, was 19. He married Maud Francis before 2 November 1381, in Middlesex, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died on 2 November 1381, in London, England, at the age of 59, and was buried in City of London, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"about 1323–2 November 1381":"umbes 1323–2. november 1381","1323–1381":"1323–1381","1362–1424":"1362–1424","1382–1424":"1382–1424","1351–1420":"1351–1420","1352–1416":"1352–1416","1295–1325":"1295–1325","1305–1326":"1305–1326","2 November 1381":"2. november 1381","1352":"1352","18 July 1326":"18. juuli